`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/run/` owns the machinery that actually launches `claude` inside a caged container and manages its lifetime: generating the preflight shell fragment and invocation command line, giving the child process a working PTY when interactive, waiting out relay-bind races, and producing the post-run diagnostic summary. Depending on this directory gets you the full "run one claude session" pipeline; callers don't assemble these pieces themselves.

The cross-cutting contract is the shell-variable handoff between `preflight.rs`'s `snippet()` and `claude_invocation()`: `snippet()` populates `$SYSTEM_PROMPT_FILE` and `$PREFLIGHT`, and `claude_invocation()`'s `--append-system-prompt-file`/headless-vs-interactive branching assumes that file already exists — the two must change together even though nothing enforces it at compile time. `pty/` is invoked only when `claude_invocation()`'s interactive branch runs and stdin is a real tty; `run_on_pty`'s `Ok(None)`/`Ok(Some)` split is what lets the parent module fall back to stdio inheritance in the non-tty case. The `setsid --ctty --wait` wrapping in `claude_invocation()` and the PTY session-leader/foreground-pgrp behavior verified in `tests.rs` are two halves of the same fix (ADR-048) — changing one without the other reintroduces the Node busy-spin bug under `--unshare-pid`.

`tests.rs` also validates a separate relay-bind-race probe (`wait_for_relay_snippet`) that isn't otherwise described in any child file here, only in its own test names — it must use `/proc/net/tcp` polling and never a real `accept()`, since real relays would forward probe connections into the host proxy. `tests/diagnostic.rs` pins the exact string output of `proxy_diagnostic`, the run's post-session summary; any format change there requires a matching implementation change.

No intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence check is possible.